hman entertains with her acidly witty observations of backstage power dynamics and faculty politics, but ultimately Wannabe U is a hard-hitting account of how higher education’s misguided pursuit of success fails us all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aUniversities and collegesxAccountingxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxAdministrationxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxBusiness managementxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxFacultyxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAccounting. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdministration. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxBusiness management. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxFaculty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  auniversity, college, higher education, administration, educational values, dean, provost, capitalism, job training, auditing, accountability, sociology, surveillance, control, quantifiable, measurements, assessment, corporatization, students, faculty, nonfiction, success, business management, accounting, evaluation, centralization, compliance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022681529940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226815282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226815282/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles